   <div class="glosses">
      <span id="INTRODUCTIONTOFRANCEGLOSS"><i>Introduction to France</i>&#x2014;<span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> adopts a picturesque view of <span class="placeName-CALAIS">Calais</span>, as compared with a practical view, 
                    which in some guidebooks takes the form of complaints about difficulties that British travelers experience in 
                    negotiating customs and finding lodging; see, for example, 
                    <i>Heath&#x02BC;s Picturesque Annual for 1832</i>, which warns that, in <span class="placeName-CALAIS">Calais</span>, 
                    &#x201C;the communication between the strangers and natives is full of strife and wrangling or silent bitterness&#x201D; 
                    (<a href="../bibiliography/bibliography.php#HEATHSANNUAL1832" target="_blank" class="inactive">Ritchie, <i>Travelling Sketches in the North of Italy, the Tyrol, and on the Rhine</i></a>, 3). 
                    Similarly, <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>&#x02BC;s account turns the abrupt transition from English character to French, separated only by the <span class="geogName-ENGLISHCHANNEL">Channel</span> crossing, into a topic for romance, 
                    whereas <span class="persName-JM">John Murray</span>&#x02BC;s 1836 guidebook remarks that <span class="placeName-CALAIS">Calais</span> &#x201C;is half Anglicised and our language is generally spoken&#x201D; 
                    (<a href="../bibiliography/bibliography.php#MURRAYSHANDBOOKCONTINENT1836" target="_blank" class="inactive"><i>Hand-book for Travellers on the Continent</i></a>, 86). 
                    <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>&#x02BC;s picturesque commentary on <span class="placeName-">Calais</span> as a place of arrival 
                    corresponds to <a href="../notes/rogers_samuel_note.php" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="persName-SR">Samuel Rogers</span></a>&#x02BC;s trope 
                    of entering a foreign scene through a city gate in &#x201C;The Lake of Geneva,&#x201C; 
                    the poem that opens <i>Italy</i>. <span class="persName-SR">Rogers</span> alludes to <span class="persName-JJRPHILOSOPHER">Jean&#x2010;Jacques Rousseau</span>&#x02BC;s (1712&#x2013;78)) 
                    story in the <i>Confessions</i> (1782&#x2013;89) in which, 
                    at age sixteen during his apprenticeship to a tyrannical watchmaker, 
                    <span class="persName-JJRPHILOSOPHER">Jean&#x2010;Jacques</span> returned to <span class="placeName-GENEVA">Geneva</span> from a country excursion too late to reenter the city gates; 
                    in despair over the punishment his master would inflict on him for his lack of restraint and discipline, 
                    the youth determines to exile himself from his native city. Following this evocation, <span class="persName-SR">Rogers</span> reverses the trope 
                    to imagine youths entering <span class="placeName-LONDON">London</span>&#x02BC;s city gates with hope&#x2014;first, 
                    <a href="../notes/chatterton_thomas.php" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="persName-TCPOET">Thomas Chatterton</span> (1752&#x2010;70)</a>, 
                    a youth more ill&#x02BC;fated even than <span class="persName-JJRPHILOSOPHER">Rousseau</span>; 
                    and then <span class="persName-DG">David Garrick</span> (1717&#x2013;79) and 
                    <span class="persName-SJ">Samuel Johnson</span> (1709&#x2013;84), destined respectively for fame and neglect 
                    (<a href="../bibiliography/bibliography.php#ROGERSITALY1830" target="_blank" class="inactive">Rogers, <i>Italy</i> (1830)</a>, 1&#x2013;3; and see 
                    <a href="../bibiliography/bibliography.php#ROUSSEAUCONFESSIONS" target="_blank" class="inactive">Rousseau, <i>Confessions</i></a>, 49 &#x005B;bk. 1&#x005D;).
                </span><br><br>
      
      <span id="FOURHOURSGLOSS"><i>Four hours</i>&#x2014;Steamers from <span class="geogName-DOVERCLF">Dover</span> to <span class="placeName-CALAIS">Calais</span> averaged, according to <span class="persName-JM">John Murray</span>&#x02BC;s 1836 guidebook, 
                    two&#x2010;and&#x2010;a&#x2010;half hours for the crossing  
                    (<a href="../bibiliography/bibliography.php#MURRAYSHANDBOOKCONTINENT1836" target="_blank" class="inactive"><i>Hand-book for Travellers on the Continent</i></a>, 86). 
                    From the <span class="placeName-TOWEROFLONDON">Tower of London</span> to <span class="placeName-CALAIS">Calais</span>, the trip lasted twelve hours, according to <span class="persName-JM">Murray</span>&#x02BC;s as well as to <span class="persName-MSA">Mariana Starke</span>&#x02BC;s 1833 guidebook 
                    (<a href="../bibiliography/bibliography.php#STARKETRAVELSINEUROPE" target="_blank" class="inactive">Starke, <i>Travels in Europe</i></a>, 526). See also 
                    <a href="../notes/tour_of_1833_note.php" target="_blank" class="inactive">Tour of 1833</a>.</span><br><br>
      
